and set `appender.close` after testing. It seems like I could override `createServerSocket` to return a wrapper that blocks when closing. But then, the outer logic sets `serverSocket` to null after closing, which complicates things. What if `serverSocket.close` is called in `stopMonitor`, then sets null right after close returns? I really need to think this through before moving forward!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test file considerations**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether to just mention the created test file while noting the existing untracked metadata directory. It might be best to keep things concise. However, I need to consider that the new test imports `java.net.Socket` but doesn't use a timeout. What if the connection fails? That could lead to future failures dragging out longer than necessary. I should really keep an eye on this to ensure robustness in the tests.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Finalizing documentation approach**\\n\\nI’m considering documenting code without being too verbose, keeping comments to a minimum aside from the license. I need to clarify that we didn’t actually compile or run the code. It looks like the bash file is okay, and I’ve added a new test file, but we haven't run any tests as per the instructions. It’s important to ensure that I communicate this clearly in the final response!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented coverage-focused test for `org.apache.log4j.net.SocketHubAppender`.\n\nAdded:\n\n- `tests/src/ch.qos.reload4j/reload4j/1.2.19/src/test/java/ch_qos_reload4j/reload4j/SocketHubAppenderTest.java`\n\nWhat it covers:\n\n- Starts a `SocketHubAppender` on a loopback ephemeral port.\n- Connects a client using `ObjectInputStream`.\n- Calls `SocketHubAppender.append(...)` with a `LoggingEvent`.\n- Verifies the serialized event is received and includes expected logger, level, message, application property, thread name, and location info.\n\nThis should execute the remaining uncove